  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Linking capital, Malawian entrepreneurs and smallholder farmers.</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In 2009 MicroEnterprise Africa (MEA) and two Malawian social entrepreneurs purchased 500 acres of former tobacco land, cleared it and are building a commercial farm which is set to make its first operating profit in 2013. Commercial farms in Malawi often contract with farmers but do not aim to empower them, only profit from them. This project aims to turn a commercial farm into a resource centre for local subsistence farmers, about 70% of whom with no formal support systems, live below the poverty line and 40% below the extreme poverty line. It will help build a smallholder farmer association made up of 50 groups of around 15 farmers each, who live in villages near the commercial farm, increasing farmers&apos; incomes by at least 50% over four years, and shortening the &#xE2;&#x20AC;&#x2DC;food gap&apos; &#xE2;&#x20AC;&#x201C; the period when families in this area have neither crops to eat nor cash to buy food for the household. The project will fund dedicated personnel to support each farming family to select and grow crops which will be marketed alongside the output of the commercial farm. Each family will receive seeds, fertiliser and specialist technical support to grow products for the commercial farm to sell. The village groups will also be supported to develop their internal procedures and financial management skills as village organisations, and over three years will be helped to develop an independent association of all the groups with a seat for a local representative on the Board of the commercial farm. Small holder interests will be channelled through a smallholder advisory committee made up of leaders and representatives of each group to MEA which owns 50% of the farm.</narrative>
  </description>
